mples: {before:,} -> {df_final.shape[0]:,} rows\")"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"8jqrHHmFDejp","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781616308865,"user_tz":-540,"elapsed":460,"user":{"displayName":"Shinwoo Noh","userId":"07027261604986966181"}},"outputId":"c205bc36-b4eb-4ad1-d10a-45fa89099aa7"},"execution_count":16,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Collapsed co-located samples: 378,513 -> 314,517 rows\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"3c045257"},"source":["### Note on Imputation Strategy\n","\n","Following the refinement process, we have elected to **preserve the NaNs** in the final tabular dataset rather than applying a global imputation (like mean or median).\n","\n","**Justification:**\n","1. **Model Flexibility**: Modern gradient boosting algorithms (like XGBoost or LightGBM) can handle missing values natively. Forcing a value now would overwrite this capability.\n","2. **Geological Integrity**: In mineral exploration, a 'missing' assay often implies the absence of visible mineralization. Imputing with a mean would artificially inflate the 'background' signal in sterile areas.\n","3. **Downstream Choice**: This dataset remains 'raw' enough for different users to apply their own supervised or unsupervised techniques. Depending on the model, one might later choose to:\n","    - Use **Spatial KNN Imputation** (filling based on the nearest neighbors).\n","    - Use **Constant Imputation** (e.g., filling with the 10th percentile as a 'low background').\n","    - Leave as **NaN** to let the model learn the significance of the missingness itself."]},{"cell_type":"code","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"1R5HEY_rYBKJ","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781616310303,"user_tz":-540,"elapsed":4,"user":{"displayName":"Shinwoo Noh","userId":"07027261604986966181"}}},"execution_count":16,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":35